c web-server

This c web-server  is a lightweight, production-style HTTP/1.1 web server written entirely in pure C11 using POSIX sockets. It has zero external dependencies — only the C standard library and POSIX APIs are used.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate how a real HTTP server works from the ground up: raw TCP sockets, manual HTTP request parsing, routing, response building, static file serving, and structured logging — all implemented without any framework or library abstractions.

Architecture

                                    Client (Browser / curl / Postman)
                                            │
                                            │  TCP Connection
                                            ▼
                                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                                    │              server.c               │
                                    │  socket() → bind() → listen()       │
                                    │  accept() → read() → close()        │
                                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘
                                                │  raw HTTP bytes
                                                ▼
                                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                                    │               http.c                │
                                    │  http_parse_request()               │
                                    │  → method, path, headers, body      │
                                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘
                                                │  HttpRequest struct
                                                ▼
                                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                                    │              router.c               │
                                    │  router_dispatch()                  │
                                    │  → match method + path              │
                                    │  → call handler function            │
                                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘
                                                │  int client_fd + HttpRequest*
                                                ▼
                                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                                    │          handler function           │
                                    │  (defined in server.c)              │
                                    │  → build JSON / HTML response       │
                                    │  → http_send_json() / html()        │
                                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘
                                                │  HTTP response bytes
                                                ▼
                                            Client receives response


Request Lifecycle

1. Client opens a TCP connection to the server
2. accept() returns a client file descriptor
3. read() reads the raw HTTP request bytes into a buffer
4. http_parse_request() parses the buffer into an HttpRequest struct
5. The router matches the method and path to a registered handler
6. The handler builds a response and writes it to the client file descriptor
7. The connection is closed


How to Get Started

Requirements
GCC     9+      C compiler
make    3.8+    Build system
bash    4+      Running testing script

On Ubuntu / Debian:
```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install gcc make curl -y
```

On macOS (with Homebrew):
```bash
brew install gcc make curl
```

Build and Run
```bash
# git clone
git clone https://github.com/username/cwebserver.git
cd cweb-server

# Compiler
make

# Run on port default 8080
./web_server

```

Stop the Server
Press Ctrl+C. The server handles SIGINT and SIGTERM cleanly — it shuts down the router, closes the socket, and flushes the log file.

